Brief justification: Let c_x = x f(x). From P(x,0) we get f(c_x) = f(0) + x^2; one can prove f(0)=0 and f(-x) = -f(x). Then f(y+c_x) = f(y) + x^2 and f(c_x) = x^2 imply, for nonzero x,y, that f(x)/x = f(y)/y, so f(t) = S t for all t with some S ∈ Q. Substituting yields S^2 = 1, hence S = ±1. Therefore f(x) = x or f(x) = -x for all x ∈ Q.
\boxed{f(x)=x \quad\text{for all } x\in\mathbb{Q} \quad\text{or}\quad f(x)=-x \quad\text{for all } x\in\mathbb{Q}}

