Partition the 100×100 board into 50×50 blocks of size 2×2; nonattacking condition forces exactly one king per block. Encode each block by A_{p,q}=1 if the king is in the top row (0 if bottom) and B_{p,q}=1 if in the left column (0 if right). Row/column sums give ∑_q A_{p,q}=25 for each block-row p and ∑_p B_{p,q}=25 for each block-column q. Nonadjacency forces each block-row’s B-sequence to be monotone 1…10…0, hence exactly 25 block-rows are all-ones and 25 all-zeros (choose which 25), and by symmetry exactly 25 block-columns have A all-ones (choose which 25). Each choice yields a unique placement, so the total number is
\boxed{\binom{50}{25}^{2}}

